passages.text: F2Q26 review: ISG margins miss on AI servers, trad'l servers, storage, but F2H improving
DELL 12m Price Target: \(\) 150.00\(Price:\) \ \(134.05\) Upside: \(11.9\%\)

DELL's EPS of \(\) 2.32\(beat GS/consensus (Visible Alpha) of\) \ \(2.26 /\) 2.29 as a beat in CSG EBIT and other income more than offset a miss in ISG EBIT driven by weaker traditional server/storage and despite AI server outperformance. F2026 EPS guidance was raised to \(\) 9.30- \ \(9.80 (v.\) \ \(9.15- \ \(9.65 prior) on better EBIT (+10% yoy v. +9% yoy prior). Key themes from the quarter include strong AI server demand, weak but improving AI server margins, weaker traditional server and storage, and mixed PC results.

First, the ISG revenue beat, combined with F2026 revenue guidance raise to \(\) 105- \ \(109 bn (v.\) \ \(101- \ \(105 bn) driven largely by a\) \ \(5 bn\) improvement in the AI server outlook to \(\) 20 bn\(, is showing limited revenue flow- through to EBIT. Said differently, F2026 revenue guidance is improved by\) \ \(4 bn\) with only \(\sim\) 100 mn of EBIT upside (implies 2% incremental margins). Although AI server mix is likely a drag on margins, the underperformance in traditional servers and storage is masking improving AI server margins in F2H26. Second, ISG margins of 8.8% missed GS/consensus of 9.6%/9.4% reflecting underperformance in traditional servers and storage (both sub- seasonal growth, which was expected, to be fair) as well as worse- than- expected AI server margins that was hurt by heightened competition in early Blackwell deals, one- time expedite costs, and geopolitical/supply chain resiliency costs. AI server margins should improve in F2H26 given the absence of these headwinds. Third, CSG revenue missed, but EBIT was better on favorable commodity costs and strong SMB demand. CSG margins should improve in F2H v. F1H given by revenue growth and share gains.
Continued AI server demand strength, with strengthening enterprise & sovereign opportunities to improve margins. During F2Q26, Dell generated \(\) 5.6\(bn in AI Server orders (v.\) \ \(12.1\)

bn in F1Q26), with \(\) 8.2\(bn in shipments (v.\) \ \(1.8\) bn in F1Q26), resulting in a backlog of \(\) 11.7\(bn. The company's AI pipeline continues to represent multiples of its backlog and represents a mix of Blackwell and older chip generations. ISG margins missed in the quarter (\) 8.8\% \(v. GS/consensus\) \uparrow 6\% /9.4\% \(), in part due to higher mix of lower - margin AI server revenue, competitive pricing, as well as one - time costs incurred in F2Q26 associated with supply chain resiliency and expediting GB200 deployments. That said, DELL believes that ISG and AI server margins should improve in F2H26, largely driven by (1) the ability of non - recurring costs incurred in F2Q26; and (2) the company's expectations for growing enterprise and sovereign AI customer mix, to whom DELL expects to attach greater amounts of higher margin services, networking, and storage solutions. Notably, DELL's enterprise and sovereign pipeline comprises over 6,700 customers and grew \(\) 0.7\%\(in the quarter, faster than that of CSPs. Additionally, F2Q26 marked the greatest quarterly revenue from AI solutions sold to enterprise customers to - date and represented the single largest number of customers DELL sold to in the quarter. The company's enterprise AI customer pipeline represents\) 50\%\$ new and \(50\%\) returning customers, across tech, manufacturing, engineering, higher education, and health care verticals.

Storage missed GS expectations & DELL lowered its outlook for storage to flat for F2026 v. LSD% growth prior, driven by weaker demand from large accounts in the United States. That said, DELL saw strong momentum in its owned IP, with double digit growth in PowerStore. Second, traditional server demand in North America (DELL's most profitable region) was also challenged in the quarter as federal spending continues to be weak, though demand grew in all other regions. DELL expects traditional servers to grow in F2H26 - though at a more muted level than expected at the beginning of the year when DELL guided to FY26 share gains in a \~LSD% growth end market - driven by the ongoing refresh opportunity, as \~70% of DELL's installed base of traditional servers is on 14G or older. Third, guidance implies that ISG performance is weighted towards F4Q. Specifically, DELL's guidance for: (1) ISG growth in the low 20s% for F3Q26; (2) mid to high 20s% for FY2026; and (3) YTD ISG performance implies that F4Q ISG revenue growth should be in the high 20s% yoy. Further, DELL's comments that AI server shipments will be slightly weighted towards the third quarter imply an even larger contribution from traditional servers and storage in F4Q26.

F2H26. During the quarter, CSG revenue of \(\) 12.5\(bn missed GSe/consensus\) \ \(13.0 /\) 12.9 bn. Within Commercial, revenue grew 2% yoy driven by ongoing Windows- 10 end- of- life driven refresh, with DD% yoy growth in EMEA, as well as growth (but at a lower rate) in North America & APJ. Within Consumer, revenue declined 7% yoy, but DELL notes profitability improved due to better execution and a deflationary environment. As such, CSG margins of 6.4% beat GS/consensus 5.7%/5.9%, largely driven by strong demand growth within SMB customers and deflationary costs. For F2026 overall, DELL reiterated its expectation to see low- to- mid single digit growth yoy in CSG driven by both Windows 10 end- of- life and the aging installed base of PCs, with expectations to gain share within the PC market and improve margins in F2H26. In- line with HPQ, DELL estimates half of the PC installed base has not yet refreshed to
Windows 11, representing substantial remaining refresh opportunity.

Dell's F2Q26 EPS of \(2.32\) beat GS/consensus (FactSet) of \(\) 2.26/\(\) 2.29\(and was in - line with guidance of\) \ \(2.15 -\) \(\) 2.35\$
DELL's F2Q26 revenue of \(\) 29,776\(mn beat GS/consensus of\) \ \(29,548 /\) 29,016 mn (v. company guidance \(\) 28.5- \(\) 29.5\(bn) driven by:

Infrastructure Solutions Group revenue of \(\) 16,800\(mn beat GSe/consensus\) \ \(15,984 /\) 15,636 mn. Server & Networking revenue of \(\) 12,944\(mn beat our estimate of\) \ \(12,010\) mn, and Storage revenue of \(\) 3,856\(mn was just under our estimate of\) \ \(3,974\) mn.

Client Solutions Group revenue of \(\) 12,503\(mn missed GSe/consensus of\) \ \(12,964 /\) 12,872 mn. Commercial revenue of \(\) 10,781\(mn missed our estimate of\) \ \(11,574\) mn, and Consumer revenue of \(\) 1,722\(mn beat our estimate of\) \ \(1,390\) mn.
Gross profit of \(\) 5,572\(mn was just under GSe/consensus\) \ \(5,614 /\) 5,682 mn, with margins of \(18.7\%\) down sequentially from F1Q26 \(21.6\%\) and below
GSe/consensus \(19.0\% /19.6\%\)

- EBIT of \(\) 2,284\(mn was in - line with GS / consensus of\) \ \(2,269 /\) 2,290 mn. Infrastructure Solutions Group EBIT of \(\) 1,470\(mn was in - line on a dollar basis (v. GS / consensus of\) \ \(1,527 /\) 1,476 mn), but margins of \(8.8\%\) missed (v. GS/consensus of \(9.6\% /9.4\%\) ). Client Solutions Group EBIT of \(\) 803\(mn was just below GSe / consensus on a dollar basis\) (\\(739 /\) 756 mn), but beat on a margin basis (6.4% v. GS/consensus \(5.7\% /5.9\%\) ).
- DELL generated \(\) 5.6\(bn in Al orders during the quarter (v.\) \ \(12.1\) bn in F1Q26), with backlog at \(\) 11.7\(bn. DELL shipped\) \ \(8.2\) bn Al server shipments during the quarter.

DELL provided guidance for F3Q26 including: (1) F3Q26 revenue between \(\) 26.5- \(\) 27.5\(bn (v. consensus\) \ \(26.4\) bn); (2) F3Q26 Non- GAAP EPS \(\) 2.45\(at midpoint (v. consensus\) \ \(2.55\) ); and (3) F3Q26 GAAP EPS \(\) 2.07\(at midpoint. By segment: (a) combined ISG and CSG should grow\) 13\% \(yoy; (b) ISG revenue should grow low - twenties\%\) yoy; (c) CSG revenue to grow MSD\% yoy; (d) Non - GAAP opex declining LSD\% yoy; (e) Non - GAAP EBIT growing \(\sim 7\%\) yoy; and (f) diluted share count \(\sim 681\) mn shares.

DELL updated F2026 guidance including: (1) revenue between \(\) 105- \(\) 109\(bn (v.\) \ \(101 - \) 105 bn); (2) non - GAAP EPS \(\) 9.55\(at midpoint (v.\) \ \(9.40\) prior); and (3) EPS \(\) 7.98\(at midpoint. By segment: (a) combined ISG and CSG to grow\) 14\% \(yoy (v. 10\% midpoint prior); (b) ISG revenue to grow mid - to - high twenties with storage flat (v. ISG growth in the high teens\) \% \(prior); (c) Al server shipments of\) \ \(20\) bn; (d) CSG revenue growing low - to - mid single digits yoy (reiterate); (e) Non - GAAP opex declining LSD\% yoy (reiterate); (f) Non - GAAP EBIT growth of \(\sim 10\%\) yoy (v. \(9\%\) prior); and (g) Interest & Other between \(\) 1.4- \(\) 1.5\(bn (reiterate).

We are Buy- rated on DELL with a 12- month target price of \(\) 150\((v.\) \ \(140\) prior) based on 13.0X (unchanged) our NTM+1Y EPS.

Key risks include: Weaker than expected consumer and commercial PC market demand; Worse- than- expected enterprise IT spending; headwinds from hybrid work could result in reduced spending in enterprise IT; Macroeconomic weakness could result in lowered consumer demand; Pricing pressure could occur as competitors discount due to excess channel inventory and reduced demand; Competition from white box manufacturers could occur, particularly in servers and storage.

Investment thesis summary. Dell Technologies (DELL) designs, manufactures, and sells information technology infrastructure and related software for servers, storage, and personal computers. Dell is a market leader in the x86 servers and storage market, and a provider of PCs and related peripherals and services for consumers & enterprises. In our view, DELL's diversified portfolio positions the company to benefit from (1) an inflection in industry PC trends driving growth in CSG segment revenue, which should also benefit from product innovation in higher- end PCs and greater exposure to commercial PCs; (2) a return to growth in the ISG segment following a rebasing of estimates, with DELL's market leading position in enterprise servers & storage positioning the company to be an IT partner- of- choice, which should help it maintain or gain share across key enterprise categories; and (3) shareholder friendly capital return
programs, including at least 40- 60% FCF return of capital to shareholders.

The Goldman Sachs Factor Profile provides investment context for a stock by comparing key attributes to the market (i.e. our universe of rated stocks) and its sector peers. The four key attributes depicted are: Growth, Financial Returns, Multiple (e.g. valuation) and Integrated (a composite of Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple). Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple are calculated by using normalized ranks for specific metrics for each stock. The normalized ranks for the metrics are then averaged and converted into percentiles for the relevant attribute. The precise calculation of each metric may vary depending on the fiscal year, industry and region, but the standard approach is as follows:

Growth is based on a stock's forward- looking sales growth, EBITDA growth and EPS growth (for financial stocks, only EPS and sales growth), with a higher percentile indicating a higher growth company. Financial Returns is based on a stock's forward- looking ROE, ROCE and CROCI (for financial stocks, only ROE), with a higher percentile indicating a company with higher financial returns. Multiple is based on a stock's forward- looking P/E, P/B, price/dividend (P/D), EV/EBITDA, EV/FCF and EV/Debt Adjusted Cash Flow (DACF) (for financial stocks, only P/E, P/B and P/D), with a higher percentile indicating a stock trading at a higher multiple. The Integrated percentile is calculated as the average of the Growth percentile, Financial Returns percentile and (100% - Multiple percentile).

Financial Returns and Multiple use the Goldman Sachs analyst forecasts at the fiscal year- end at least three quarters in the future. Growth uses inputs for the fiscal year at least seven quarters in the future compared with the year at least three quarters in the future (on a per- share basis for all metrics).
For a more detailed description of how we calculate the GS Factor Profile, please contact your GS representative.
